Functional and Non functional requirements

Requirement analysis is a crucial step in software development where the needs and expectations of users and stakeholders are identified
and documented. It ensures that the system being built will meet its intended goals and correct functionality.
Based on the requirements it is of two types:
1. Functional Requirments (defines What the system should perform)
2. Non Functional Requirements ( defines how the system should perform)

Functional Requirements :

-> It defines the specific features and operatios a system must perform to meet business and user needs.
-> They describe what the system do and how it interacts.
-> Focus on the behaviour and functionality of the system.
-> Represents features that can be easily observed and tested in the final product.
-> Examples include user authentication, data processing, payment processing and report generation.

Non Functional Requirements :

-> It defines how the system should operate focusing on performance, reliability and user experience rather than a specific feature.
-> It include performance => speed and responsiveness , security => protection against unauthorized access, 
 Reliability -> availability and system stability , Usability => ease of use, Maintainability -> easy updates and fixes,
portability => Able to run in different environments, scalability => able to handle growth.

Extended Requirements:

-> Extended requirements define additional capabilities or considerations that enhance the system but not teh core functional freatures.
-> This includes monitoring, reliability and future entension of the system such as

  1. Logging  => Recording system activities and errors for debugging and analysis.
  2. Monitoring & Alerting => Tracking system health, performance amd failures
  3. Analytics => collect usage data to understand user behaviour and system performance
  4. Backup & Disaster discovery => Ensuring data can be restored in case of failures.
  5. Rate limiting => Controlling the number of requests to prevent system overload or abuse.
  6. Feature flags / A-B Testing => Enabling controlled feature releases and experiements.

Examples of functional and non functional requirements :

Online Banking System

1. Functional Requirements
   -> User should withdraw money and check balance.
   -> User should login into the account.
   -> User should receive notifications after making a transaction.

2. Non Functional Requirements
  -> The system should respond to user in less than 2 seconds.
  -> The system should handle 100 million requests with minimal downtime.
  -> All transactions must be encrypted and follow industry standards.

3. Extended Requirements
   -> The system should log all transactions for auditing and fraud detection.
   ->  The system should send alerts and notifications to detect unusual activities.
   -> The system should have automatic backups and disaster recovery mechanisms.
